  • U.S. Newsflare

    Wild tiger chases safari vehicle full of terrified tourists

    A group of tourists in northern India got the fright of their lives on Saturday (November 30th) when a wild tiger chased their safari vehicle. Footage filmed in Ranthambore National Park in the north Indian state of Rajasthan shows the vehicle stopped on a road with tourists photographing a tigress known as Sultana. When the tour vehicle reverses away, however, the tigress follows and then starts to chase the vehicle for about 30 metres. The driver quickly stops reversing and steps on the gas to get away but still the tiger gives chase for several metres before eventually giving up and disappearing into the undergrowth. Some local reports blamed the expansion of tourism for the unusual behaviour of the big cat, suggesting that the felines are angered by the constant stream of safari vehicles.

    Reusable plastic shopping bags are actually making the problem worse, not better

    Over the past few years, reusable plastic shopping bags began showing up in grocery stores in many parts of the world. Because no matter the style of plastic bag, it will still contribute to the global problem of forever-trash entering the environment, and the greenhouse gases associated with manufacturing the bag from fossil fuels in the first place. A new report from the Environmental Investigation Agency (EIA) and Greenpeace looking at grocery stores in the UK suggests that the plastic bags for life utterly failed to do the one thing they were ostensibly meant to.
